{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Massachusetts", "text_new": "{{short description|Ongoing viral pandemic in Massachusetts}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Current event|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Massachusetts\n| map1            = COVID-19 cases in Massachusetts per capita map.svg\n| legend1         = Cases per 100,000 people as of March 31{{Col-begin}}{{Col-2}}{{legend|#C8C8C8|0}}{{legend|#FFE4A3|1\u20139}}{{legend|#F2A88D|10\u201349}}{{Col-2}}{{legend|#E57814|50\u2013199}}{{legend|#FF0000|200\u2013499}}{{legend|#A81C1B|&#8805; 500}}{{Col-end}}\n| location        = [[Massachusetts]], United States\n| first_case      = [[Boston]]\n| disease         = [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| arrival_date    = February 1, 2020\n| confirmed_cases = 6620<ref name=\"Mass-DPH\">{{cite web | title = COVID-19 Cases, Quarantine and Monitoring | url = https://www.mass.gov/info-details/covid-19-cases-quarantine-and-monitoring | website = Massachusetts Department of Public Health | access-date = March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n| active_cases    = 6463\n| recovery_cases  = 68 <ref name=\"Boston.gov\">{{cite web | url = https://dashboard.cityofboston.gov/t/Guest_Access_Enabled/views/COVID-19/Dashboard1|title=Boston COVID-19 Dashboard|access-date = March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n| deaths          = 89 as of March 31, 2020\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], Hubei, China\n| website         = [https://www.mass.gov/resource/information-on-the-outbreak-of-coronavirus-disease-2019-covid-19 Information on the Outbreak of Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) from the Massachusetts Department of Health]\n}}\nThe '''2020 coronavirus pandemic in Massachusetts''' is part of an [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|ongoing pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) in the US state of [[Massachusetts]].  The first confirmed case was reported on February 1, 2020, and cases began growing rapidly on March 5.  [[Governor of Massachusetts|Governor]] [[Charlie Baker]] declared a state of emergency on March 10, and by March 12, over 100 people were infected. Most early cases were traceable to a [[Biogen]] conference held in [[Boston]] in late February. {{As of|2020|03|31|df=US}}, Massachusetts had 6,620 cases, 562 hospitalizations, and 89 deaths due to COVID-19.<ref name=\"Mass-DPH\" />\n\nSchool closures began March 9, when [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] (MIT) moved large classes to only-online for the rest of the semester,<ref name=\"MIT-Update\">{{cite web | url = http://web.mit.edu/covid19/update-to-undergraduates/ | title = Update to Undergraduate Students | date = March 9, 2020 | website = [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] | access-date = March 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Covid-19 Response | website = [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] | date = March 14, 2020 | url = http://web.mit.edu/covid19/ | access-date = March 15, 2020}}</ref> and a handful of local schools closed. By March 13, many colleges and state school districts announced closures ranging from weeks to months in duration.<ref name=\"Williams-Update\">{{cite web | last = Williams | first = Michelle | title = Massachusetts coronavirus update: Schools closing or changing schedules for Monday, March 16 | website = MassLive | date = March 13, 2020 | url = https://www.masslive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/massachusetts-coronavirus-update-schools-closing-or-changing-schedules-for-monday-march-16.html | access-date = March 15, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Williams-Colleges\">{{cite web | title = Coronavirus and Massachusetts: Updated list of Massachusetts colleges with canceled classes, plans to switch to online instruction (March 13) | date = March 14, 2020 | first = Michelle | last = Williams | publisher = MassLive | url = https://www.masslive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-and-massachusetts-updated-list-of-massachusetts-colleges-with-canceled-classes-plans-to-switch-to-online-instruction-march-13.html}}</ref>\n\nOn March 15, Baker ordered all schools in Massachusetts closed for three weeks from March 17, through April 7.  The same day, he also banned eating at restaurants, banned gatherings of over 25 people, relaxed unemployment claim requirements, and enacted other interventions through April 17, to slow the spread of COVID-19.<ref name=\"Becker\" /> On March 23, Governor Baker enacted a stay-at-home advisory until April 7, which was extended to May 4, to further inhibit the spread of COVID-19.<ref name=\"Feuer\" /> Two days later, Baker extended the closure period of schools, ordering them to remain closed through May 4.<ref name=\"nbcboston1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcboston.com/news/local/gov-baker-to-provide-coronavirus-update/2096962/|title=Baker Extends School and Day Care Closures|website=NBC Boston|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Massachusetts medical cases chart}}\n\n== Timeline ==\n\n=== February ===\n[[File:Marriott Long Wharf hotel; west and south sides; Boston, MA; 2020-03-14.jpg|thumb|right|Most early COVID-19 cases in Massachusetts traced to a [[Biogen]] conference held in late February at Marriott Long Wharf hotel in Boston, pictured here.]]\n\nThe first case of COVID-19 was confirmed by state health officials on February 1. Massachusetts became the 2nd state in America to report a case of coronavirus. The individual, a [[University of Massachusetts Boston]] student, had returned to Boston from [[Wuhan]], China. Upon returning to Boston he began experiencing symptoms and sought medical care. University of Massachusetts Boston Interim Chancellor [[Katherine Newman]] addressed the situation as \"business as usual\" in a campus wide email. Students and faculty were assured they were at no risk, even though a confirmed case was identified.<ref name=\"Wertheim\" />\n\n175 executives of [[Biogen Inc]]., a biotechnology company based in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge]], held a two-day leadership conference from February 26\u201328 at the Boston Marriott Long Wharf hotel.<ref name=\"Arsenault\">{{Cite news | last = Arsenault | first = Mark | url = https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/03/11/nation/how-biogen-leadership-conference-boston-spread-coronavirus/ | title = How the Biogen leadership conference in Boston spread the coronavirus | date = March 10, 2020 | work = [[The Boston Globe]] | access-date = March 13, 2020 | last2 = Rosen | first2 = Andy | last3 = Krueger | first3 = Hanna | last4 = Lazar | first4 = Kay | last5 = Saltzman | first5 = Jonathan | last6 = Kowalczyk | first6 = Liz}}</ref> On February 29, a [[Biogen]] executive began to develop symptoms and sought treatment at a Boston area hospital. Suspecting COVID-19 was the cause of the illness, the executive requested a test, but was told by hospital staff that it was not necessary.<ref name=\"Arsenault\" /><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.wbur.org/commonhealth/2020/03/12/coronavirus-outbreak-biogen-conference-superspreading | title = Single Conference Linked To Most Mass. Coronavirus Cases Looks Like A 'Superspreading Event' | website = [[WBUR-FM]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.nbcboston.com/news/coronavirus/boston-biogen-meeting-coronavirus-warning/2089438/ | title = Biogen Meeting Tied to Coronavirus Cases Serves as Warning}}</ref>\n\n=== March ===\n\n==== March 2\u20133 ====\nOn March 2, the second confirmed case in Massachusetts was reported.  The patient was a woman in her 20s from [[Norfolk County]].  She had recently traveled to Italy with a school group from [[Saint Raphael Academy]] in [[Pawtucket, Rhode Island|Pawtucket]], [[Rhode Island]].  She was the third person from the trip to test positive.<ref name=\"WBUR-2nd\" />\n\n==== March 4\u20135 ====\nOn March 4, staff from Biogen contacted the [[Massachusetts Department of Public Health]] (MDPH) claiming that two executives who had recently traveled from Europe to Boston and had attended the February conference had tested positive for COVID-19 upon returning home.  The same day, a \"significant number\" of Biogen employees asked for coronavirus tests at [[Massachusetts General Hospital]] (MGH), which had not been informed that anyone at the company had been exposed to COVID-19. The state police announced Shattuck Street would be closed because a group of 60 individuals were being transported along the route to [[Brigham and Women's Hospital]].<ref>{{Cite news | last = Cotter | first = Sean Philip | url = https://www.bostonherald.com/2020/03/06/bio-hazard-60-head-to-hospital-for-coronavirus-testing-in-boston/ | title = Coronavirus in Boston: 60 head to Brigham and Women's Hospital for testing | date = March 9, 2020 | work = [[Boston Herald]] | access-date = March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 5, Biogen reported that three individuals who had attended a company event in Boston the previous week had tested positive for SARS-CoV-2.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Fortier | first = Marc | url = https://www.nbcboston.com/news/local/3-who-attended-biogen-meeting-in-boston-test-positive-for-coronavirus/2086462/ | title = 3 Who Attended Biogen Meeting in Boston Test Positive for Coronavirus | date = March 6, 2020 | work = NBC Boston | access-date = March 13, 2020 | last2 = Rosenfield | first2 = Marc}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.nbcboston.com/news/local/3-who-attended-biogen-meeting-in-boston-test-positive-for-coronavirus/2086462/ | title = 3 Who Attended Biogen Meeting in Boston Test Positive for Coronavirus | last = Fortier | first = Marc | date = March 5, 2020 | website = [[WBTS-CD|WBTS]] | access-date = March 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== March 6\u20139 ====\nOn March 6, public health officials reported five new cases bringing the state total to eight.<ref name=\"Mass-DPH\" /><ref>{{Cite news | last = Fortier | first = Marc | url = https://www.nbcboston.com/news/coronavirus/what-we-know-about-the-coronavirus-cases-linked-to-biogens-boston-meeting/2086974/ | title = Coronavirus Cases Linked to Biogen Boston Meeting: What We Know | date = March 11, 2020 | work = NBC Boston | access-date = March 13, 2020}}</ref> Four cases were in [[Suffolk County, Massachusetts|Suffolk County]], three in [[Norfolk County, Massachusetts|Norfolk County]], and one in [[Middlesex County, Massachusetts|Middlesex County]]. Two cases were associated with travel to Italy and one to Wuhan. All five new cases were associated with the Biogen meeting.<ref name=\"Boston-25\">{{Cite news | url = https://www.boston25news.com/more/blog-latest-coronavirus-cases-news-massachusetts/XZXJA7P3J5ENZFXLRG2YUFWTSI/ | title = Boston closes Eliot School as number of COVID-19 cases in Mass. rise | work = Boston 25 News | access-date = March 13, 2020 | url-status = live | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200308003947/https://www.boston25news.com/more/blog-latest-coronavirus-cases-news-massachusetts/XZXJA7P3J5ENZFXLRG2YUFWTSI/ | archive-date = March 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.wcvb.com/article/workers-who-attended-boston-biogen-meeting-test-positive-for-coronavirus/31252079 | title = Workers who attended Boston Biogen meeting test positive for coronavirus | date = March 6, 2020 | work = WCVB | access-date = March 11, 2020 | url-status = live | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200307124523/https://www.wcvb.com/article/workers-who-attended-boston-biogen-meeting-test-positive-for-coronavirus/31252079 | archive-date = March 7, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Sheridan\">{{Cite news | last = Sheridan | first = Kate | url = https://www.statnews.com/2020/03/06/biogen-workers-test-positive-for-coronavirus-transmission-linked-to-leadership-meeting/ | title = Top Biogen execs were at meeting where attendees had Covid-19 | date = March 6, 2020 | work = STAT | access-date = March 9, 2020 | url-status = live | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200308154652/https://www.statnews.com/2020/03/06/biogen-workers-test-positive-for-coronavirus-transmission-linked-to-leadership-meeting/ | archive-date = March 8, 2020 | last2 = Feuerstein | first2 = Adam | last3 = Herper | first3 = Matthew}}</ref> [[Northeastern University]], which had already closed satellite campuses in San Francisco and Seattle, hesitated to close their main campus for fear of international students losing their [[F visa]] status, and publicly called on the [[Department of Homeland Security]] to grant clemency for international students so the University can close.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://news.northeastern.edu/coronavirus/university-messages/president-aouns-letter-to-the-u-s-department-of-homeland-security-on-f-1-student-visas/ | title = President Aoun's letter to the U.S. Department of Homeland Security on F-1 student visas | last = Aoun | first = Joseph E. | date = March 6, 2020 | website = Northeastern University}}</ref> On March 7, there were five more presumptive positive cases of COVID-19, bringing the total to 13.<ref>{{Cite news | url = https://boston.cbslocal.com/2020/03/07/coronavirus-cases-massachusetts-rises-12-presumptive-1-confirmed/ | title = Coronavirus Cases in Massachusetts Rise To 12 Presumptive, 1 Confirmed | date = March 7, 2020 | work = CBS Boston | access-date = March 13, 2020}}</ref> Among those cases was the [[index case]] in [[Berkshire County]], a man in his 60s from [[Clarksburg, Massachusetts|Clarksburg]] whose infection could not be traced.<ref name=\"WHDH-Berkshire-1st\">{{cite web | url = https://whdh.com/news/berkshire-county-is-now-being-considered-the-big-question-mark-when-it-comes-to-coronavirus-in-massachusetts/ | title = Berkshire County is now being considered the big question mark when it comes to coronavirus in Massachusetts}}</ref>\n\nOn March 8, the MDPH reported 15 more presumptive cases of COVID-19,<ref name=\"Sheridan\" /> all of which were individuals present at the Biogen conference,<ref name=\"Boston-25\" /> bringing the total to 28.<ref name=\"Mass-DPH\" /> In response to the outbreak, Biogen ordered all its employees to work from home.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Linnane | first = Ciara | url = https://www.marketwatch.com/story/biogen-orders-employees-to-work-from-home-after-employees-at-boston-meeting-test-positive-for-coronavirus-2020-03-08 | title = Biogen orders employees to work from home after employees at Boston meeting test positive for coronavirus | date = March 9, 2020 | work = MarketWatch | access-date = March 11, 2020 | url-status = live | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200308231025/https://www.marketwatch.com/story/biogen-orders-employees-to-work-from-home-after-employees-at-boston-meeting-test-positive-for-coronavirus-2020-03-08 | archive-date = March 8, 2020}}</ref> The fifteen new presumptive cases included five from Suffolk County, five from Middlesex County, four from Norfolk County, and one whose county of residence was unknown.<ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.wcvb.com/article/massachusetts-health-officials-announce-15-new-presumptive-coronavirus-cases-all-connected-to-biogen-conference/31274340 | title = Mass. announces 15 new presumptive coronavirus cases; all connected to Biogen conference | date = March 8, 2020 | work = WCVB | access-date = March 8, 2020}}</ref> On March 9, there were 13 new presumptive cases, bringing the total number of confirmed or presumptive cases in Massachusetts to 41.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Sobey | first = Rick | url = https://www.bostonherald.com/2020/03/09/coronavirus-cases-in-massachusetts-rise-to-41/ | title = Coronavirus cases in Massachusetts rise to 41 | date = March 9, 2020 | work = [[Boston Herald]] | access-date = March 13, 2020 | last2 = Cohan | first2 = Alexi}}</ref> Officials in North Carolina reported that five residents of Wake County tested positive for COVID-19; all five were participants in the previous week's Biogen conference in Boston.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Brown | first = Joell | url = https://abc11.com/5997924/ | title = 5 Wake County residents test positive for coronavirus after attending Biogen conference connected to 2 dozen cases | date = March 9, 2020 | work = abc11.com | access-date = March 13, 2020}}</ref> The Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT) announced that all large lectures would be held online only.<ref name=\"MIT-Update\" /><ref>{{Cite news | last = Fernandes | first = Deidre | url = https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/03/09/business/mit-says-all-large-classes-will-be-taught-online-amid-coronavirus-fears/ | title = MIT says all large classes will be taught online amid coronavirus fears | date = March 9, 2020 | work = [[The Boston Globe]] }}</ref>\n\n==== March 10\u201311 ====\n[[File:Out of stock at CVS on March 10, 2020.jpg|thumb|right|upright=0.9|Items out of stock at a [[CVS Pharmacy]] in [[Westford, Massachusetts]]]]\n\nOn March 10, the state reported 50 new cases of coronavirus, bringing the total to 92.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Fortier | first = Marc | url = https://www.nbcboston.com/news/local/gov-baker-to-speak-on-states-coronavirus-preparedness/2088681/ | title = Gov. Charlie Baker Declares State of Emergency as Massachusetts Coronavirus Cases Rise to 92 | date = March 10, 2020 | work = NBC Boston | access-date = March 13, 2020}}</ref> [[Harvard University]] announced that its classes would be online-only for the rest of the spring semester.<ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.thecrimson.com/article/2020/3/11/harvard-coronavirus-classes-cancelled/ | title = Harvard Moves Classes Online, Asks Students Not to Return After Spring Break in Response to Coronavirus | date = March 11, 2020 | work = [[The Harvard Crimson]] | access-date = March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | last = Carraggi | first = Mike | url = https://patch.com/massachusetts/boston/harvard-asks-students-not-return-break-amid-virus-fears | title = Harvard, Others Ask Students Not To Return From Break, Go Virtual | date = March 10, 2020 | work = Boston, MA Patch | access-date = March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://web.mit.edu/covid19/update-from-president-l-rafael-reif-to-the-mit-community/ | title = Update from President L. Rafael Reif to the MIT Community | last = Reif | first = L. Rafael | date = March 10, 2020 | website = [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] | url-status = live | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200311023015/https://web.mit.edu/covid19/update-from-president-l-rafael-reif-to-the-mit-community/ | archive-date = March 11, 2020 | access-date = March 11, 2020}}</ref> The University of Massachusetts Boston informed faculty that they should prepare to teach remotely.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Aliyu | first = Wale | url = https://www.boston25news.com/news/umass-boston-preparing-roll-out-online-classes-coronavirus-concerns-grow/76QRLNDDDRB2VGXAKLFU3OPNCU/ | title = UMass Boston preparing to roll out online classes as coronavirus concerns grow | date = March 10, 2020 | work = Boston 25 News | access-date = March 13, 2020}}</ref> [[Amherst College]], located in [[Western Massachusetts]], instructed students on spring break to not return to campus, and moved all classes online for the remainder of the semester.<ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.wcvb.com/article/coronavirus-prompts-amherst-college-to-move-to-remote-learning-for-rest-of-semester/31307851 | title = Coronavirus prompts Amherst College to move to remote learning for rest of semester | date = March 10, 2020 | work = WCVB | access-date = March 13, 2020}}</ref> [[Emerson College]], [[Tufts University]], [[Babson College]], [[Smith College]], and [[Wheaton College (Massachusetts)|Wheaton College]] all canceled in-person classes and moved classes online.<ref name=\"Corrado\">{{Cite news | last = Corrado | first = Kerri | url = https://whdh.com/news/which-mass-colleges-are-making-changes-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/ | title = Which Mass. colleges are making changes amid coronavirus outbreak? | date = March 11, 2020 | work = WHDH 7News | access-date = March 11, 2020 | last2 = Connolly | first2 = Brynne}}</ref> A man in [[Sudbury, Massachusetts|Sudbury]] tested \"presumptive positive\" for COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite news | last = McNamara | first = Neal | url = https://patch.com/massachusetts/sudbury/sudbury-resident-tests-positive-coronavirus | title = Sudbury Resident Tests Positive For Coronavirus | date = March 10, 2020 | work = Sudbury, MA Patch | access-date = March 11, 2020}}</ref>  The first case in [[Essex County, Massachusetts|Essex County]] was also reported.<ref name=\"Tribune-Essex-1st\">{{cite web|url=https://www.eagletribune.com/news/merrimack_valley/baker-important-to-start-taking-more-aggressive-actions/article_9da811ab-d265-5a93-8e7c-37b035f27e17.html|title=Baker: 'Important to start taking more aggressive actions'|author=Christian M. Wade|date=March 10, 2020|publisher=Eagle Tribune}}</ref>\n\nOn March 11, several schools were closed including Hopkinton Public Schools, Loker Elementary and [[Wayland Middle School]], and Clark Avenue Middle School.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Cho | first = Diane | url = https://www.nbcboston.com/news/coronavirus/coronavirus-concerns-shut-down-hopkinton-wayland-schools-wednesday/2089034/ | title = Multiple Mass. Schools Closed Wednesday Over Coronavirus Outbreak | date = March 11, 2020 | work = NBC Boston | access-date = March 11, 2020}}</ref> Northeastern University and [[Boston University]] moved to online classes.<ref name=\"Corrado\" /><ref>{{cite web | url = https://news.northeastern.edu/coronavirus/university-messages/advancing-our-mission-in-a-time-of-uncertainty/ | title = Advancing our Mission in a Time of Uncertainty | last = Aoun | first = Joseph E. | website = Northeastern University | access-date = March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bu.edu/articles/2020/bu-all-classes-online-coronavirus/ | title = Updated: BU Moves All Classes Online Due to Coronavirus \u2014 Questions and Answers | last = Most | first = Doug | date = March 11, 2020 | website = BU Today | access-date = March 13, 2020}}</ref> [[Williams College]] announced it would end in-person classes on Friday, March 13 and move to remote learning as of Monday, April 6.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.williams.edu/coronavirus/ | title = Coronavirus (COVID-19) | website = [[Williams College]] | access-date = March 11, 2020}}</ref> [[Boston College]] moved all classes online, and all students were told to vacate their dorms by March 15.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bc.edu/content/bc-web/sites/updates/coronavirus.html | title = Coronavirus Updates | website = [[Boston College]] | access-date = March 11, 2020}}</ref> All [[University of Massachusetts]] classes moved online until at least April 3.<ref name=\"Corrado\" />\n\n==== March 12\u201313 ====\nOn March 12, there were 108 people in Massachusetts with confirmed or presumptive cases of COVID-19.  Among those cases, 82 (75% of the total) were associates or employees of Biogen.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.mass.gov/doc/covid-19-cases-in-massachusetts-march-12-2020/download | title = Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) Cases in MA | date = March 12, 2020 | website = Massachusetts Department of Public Health | format = PDF | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200313200733/https://www.mass.gov/doc/covid-19-cases-in-massachusetts-march-12-2020/download | archive-date = March 13, 2020}}</ref> Governor Baker noted that the state had currently tested over 200 patients and had the capacity to test up to 5,000.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Becker | first = Deborah | url = https://www.wbur.org/commonhealth/2020/03/12/massachusetts-coronavirus-testing | title = State: Massachusetts Has Tested More Than 200 People For Coronavirus | date = March 12, 2020 | work = [[WBUR-FM]] | access-date = March 13, 2020 | department = CommonHealth}}</ref> The Boston Marriott Long Wharf hotel, which hosted a Biogen company gathering linked to a majority of the coronavirus cases in Massachusetts, closed temporarily. In a letter to guests on Thursday, the hotel said it made the decision with the [[Boston Public Health Commission]].<ref>{{Cite news | last = Goldberg | first = Carey | url = https://www.wbur.org/commonhealth/2020/03/12/coronavirus-outbreak-biogen-conference-superspreading | title = Single Conference Linked To Most Mass. Coronavirus Cases Looks Like A 'Superspreading Event' | date = March 12, 2020 | work = [[WBUR-FM]] | access-date = March 13, 2020 | department = CommonHealth}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | last = Borchers | first = Callum | url = https://www.wbur.org/bostonomix/2020/03/12/marriott-hotel-closed-biogen-coronavirus | title = Hotel That Hosted Biogen Gathering Tied To Coronavirus Outbreak Will Close Temporarily | date = March 12, 2020 | work = [[WBUR-FM]] | access-date = March 13, 2020 | department = Bostonomix}}</ref> [[Acton-Boxborough]] announced school closures from March 13 until March 20.<ref>{{Cite tweet | number = 1238185986603003905 | user = ABschools | title = AB Schools will be closed 3/13 \u2013 3/20. See letter below for complete details. We are experiencing issues with our mass messaging system and are requesting this be shared. | author = ABRSSD | date = March 12, 2020 | access-date = March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, the [[Boston Marathon]] was postponed from April 20, until September 14.<ref>{{cite news | last1 = Ruckstuhl | first1 = Laney | title = In A First, Boston Marathon Is Officially Postponed Until September | url = https://www.wbur.org/news/2020/03/13/boston-marathon-coronavirus-fears-postponed | access-date = March 13, 2020 | work = [[WBUR-FM]] }}</ref> A few hours later, Massachusetts Governor Charlie Baker prohibited gatherings of more than 250 people. The measure was targeted at large events and exempted most workplaces, transit buildings, polling locations, government buildings, and schools.<ref>{{cite news | last1 = Mitchell | first1 = Jack | title = Baker Bans All Gatherings Of 250 Or More People in Mass. | url = https://www.wbur.org/news/2020/03/13/baker-bans-all-gatherings-of-250-or-more-people-in-mass | access-date = March 13, 2020 | work = [[WBUR-FM]] }}</ref> [[Se\u00e1n Patrick O'Malley|Cardinal O'Malley]] announced that all daily and Sunday Masses, and other religious services would be suspended in the Archdiocese of Boston until further notice amid concerns about COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.wcvb.com/article/archdiocese-of-boston-suspends-all-daily-sunday-masses-and-religious-services/31488459 | title = Archdiocese of Boston suspends all daily, Sunday Masses and religious services | date = March 13, 2020 | website = WCVB}}</ref> In addition, [[Mayor of Boston|Boston Mayor]] [[Marty Walsh (politician)|Marty Walsh]] announced that [[Boston Public Schools]] would be closed starting on Tuesday, March 17 until April 27.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.nbcboston.com/news/local/boston-mayor-marty-walsh-coronavirus-update/2090828/ | title = Boston Public Schools to Close for Over a Month Starting Tuesday Over Coronavirus | date = March 13, 2020 | website = NBC Boston}}</ref> The MDPH announced that there were 123 cases of COVID-19 in Massachusetts.<ref name=\"Mass-DPH\" /><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.nbcboston.com/news/local/massachusetts-coronavirus-cases-up-to-123/2090658/ | title = Massachusetts Coronavirus Cases Up to 123}}</ref> [[Woburn, Massachusetts|Woburn]] announced that a presumptive positive case in the city had been confirmed as negative.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.woburnma.gov/news/2020/03/coronavirus-covid-19/ | title = Coronavirus (COVID-19)-City of Woburn | date = March 13, 2020 | website = City of Woburn}}</ref>\n\n==== March 14\u201315 ====\nOn March 14, [[Cape Cod]] ([[Barnstable County]]) confirmed its first case,<ref name=\"Barnstable-1st\">{{cite web | last1 = Treffeisen | first1 = Beth | title = Cape's first case of COVID-19 confirmed | url = https://www.capecodtimes.com/news/20200314/capes-first-case-of-covid-19-confirmed | website = [[Cape Cod Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = First case of COVID-19 on Cape | url = https://www.mvtimes.com/2020/03/14/first-case-covid-19-cape/ | website = [[The Martha's Vineyard Times]] | date = March 14, 2020}}</ref> a man in his 60s from [[Sandwich, Massachusetts|Sandwich]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.capecodtimes.com/news/20200314/sandwich-man-first-cape-case-of-covid-19 | title = Sandwich man first Cape case of COVID-19 | first = Beth | last = Treffeisen | website = [[Cape Cod Times]] }}</ref> There were 15 new cases, bringing the total number of confirmed or presumptive cases of COVID-19 in Massachusetts to 138.<ref name=\"Mass-DPH\" /> Officials in [[Worcester, Massachusetts|Worcester]] and [[Malden, Massachusetts|Malden]] both announced their respective cities' first confirmed case of COVID-19, both linked to Biogen.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.wcvb.com/article/massachusetts-coronavirus-covid-19-testing-update-march-14-2020/31552452 | title = 1st coronavirus cases in Cape Cod, Worcester among 15 new cases in Mass. | date = March 15, 2020 | website = WCVB}}</ref><ref name=\"Worcester-1st\">{{cite web | url = http://www.worcesterma.gov/announcements/covid-19-update-for-march-14-first-positive-case | title = COVID-19 Update for March 14; First Positive Case | website = City of Worcester, MA }}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet | user = TheCityOfMalden | number = 1238842398475800576 | date = March 14, 2020 | title = The Malden Health Department has been notified by the Mass Department of Public Health that a Malden resident has tested positive for Coronavirus.}}</ref> Of the state's 138 cases, 104 (75%) could be traced to employees or contacts of Biogen.<ref name=\"Mass-DPH\" />\n\nA 59-year-old Worcester man died on a flight from Dubai to Boston.<ref>{{cite web | last = Becker | first = Kaitlin McKinley | title = Massachusetts Man Who Died Aboard Flight From Dubai to Boston Will Be Tested for COVID-19 | website = NBC Boston | date = March 14, 2020 | url = https://www.nbcboston.com/news/local/massachusetts-man-who-died-aboard-flight-from-dubai-to-boston-will-be-tested-for-covid-19/2091214/ | access-date = March 15, 2020}}</ref> He had been sick with gastrointestinal problems and was in cardiac arrest during the flight.  On March 16, [[Massachusetts State Police]] said that an autopsy revealed he did not have COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web | title = Passenger who died on flight from Dubai to Boston did not have coronavirus, state police say | website = WCVB | date = March 16, 2020 | url = https://www.wcvb.com/article/passenger-died-on-international-flight-no-coronavirus-state-police-say/31674048 | access-date = March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 15, Baker ordered all public and private schools in Massachusetts closed for three weeks from March 17, through April 7.  The same day, he also banned eating at restaurants, banned gatherings of over 25 people, relaxed unemployment claim requirements, and enacted other interventions through April 17 to slow the spread of COVID-19.<ref name=\"Becker\">{{cite web | url = https://www.nbcboston.com/news/local/26-new-coronavirus-cases-in-massachusetts-164-total/2091478/ | title = Gov. Baker Closes Schools, Bans Mid-Size Gatherings, Eating at Restaurants | author = Kaitlin McKinley Becker | date = March 15, 2020}}</ref> The [[Massachusetts Department of Public Health]] (MDPH) announced that 799 residents had been tested for COVID-19, up from 475 one day prior.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.mass.gov/news/statement-from-the-massachusetts-department-of-public-health-on-patient-testing-for-covid-19 | title = Statement from the Massachusetts Department of Public Health on patient testing for COVID-19 | website = Mass.gov  | access-date = March 15, 2020}}</ref> There were 164 total cases; 45 confirmed and 119 presumptive. [[Hampden County, Massachusetts|Hampden]] and [[Plymouth County, Massachusetts|Plymouth]] counties had their first cases.<ref name=\"Mass-DPH\" /> Plymouth County's first case, in [[Hanover, Massachusetts|Hanover]], resulted from travel and the individual was doing well.<ref name=\"Plymouth-1st\">{{cite web | url = https://www.hanover-ma.gov/home/news/town-of-hanover-covid-19-update-31520 | title = Town of Hanover COVID-19 Update 3/15/20 |website=Hanover, MA |access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> Hampden County's first case tested positive at [[Baystate Medical Center]] in [[Springfield, Massachusetts|Springfield]]; the hospital noted an additional 23 suspected cases.<ref name=\"Hampden-1st\">{{cite web | url = https://www.wwlp.com/news/health/coronavirus-local-impact/baystate-medical-center-confirms-first-case-of-covid-19/ | title = First case of COVID-19 locally confirmed at Baystate Medical Center | first = Katrina | last = Kincade | date = March 14, 2020 | publisher = [[WWLP]]}}</ref>\n\n==== March 16\u201317 ====\n\nOn March 16, a student at Northeastern University tested positive for COVID-19, one day after the university ordered all students to vacate dormitories by 5:00&nbsp;p.m. on Tuesday, March 17.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://boston.cbslocal.com/2020/03/15/coronavirus-northeastern-university-student-tests-positive/ | title = Northeastern University Student Tests Positive For Coronavirus | date = March 15, 2020 | website = CBS Boston | access-date = March 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://boston.cbslocal.com/2020/03/14/coronavirus-northeastern-unversitity-students-must-leave-dorms-by-tuesday/ | title = Northeastern Reverses Decision, Says Students Must Leave Dorms For Coronavirus Prevention | date = March 14, 2020 | first = Jim | last = Smith | publisher = CBS Boston}}</ref> Up to this point students were taking online classes but allowed to remain on University property.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://news.northeastern.edu/2020/03/14/northeastern-requests-that-students-move-out-of-dorms-by-tuesday-at-5-p-m-citing-public-health-guidance/ | title = Northeastern requests that students move out of dorms by Tuesday at 5:00&nbsp;p.m., citing public health guidance | website = [[Northeastern University]] | access-date = March 16, 2020}}</ref> [[Brockton, Massachusetts|Brockton]] announced its first case, and the mayor declared a state of emergency for the city.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.enterprisenews.com/news/20200316/brockton-mayor-confirms-first-case-of-coronavirus-in-city-declares-state-of-emergency | title = Brockton mayor confirms first case of coronavirus in city; declares state of emergency | last = Larocque | first = Marc | website = The Enterprise, Brockton, MA  | access-date = March 17, 2020}}</ref> The number of cases increased to 197.\n\nBoston Mayor Marty Walsh ordered construction projects to shut down and be secured with at most skeleton crews by March 23, and that all branches of the [[Boston Public Library]] would close that night by 6:00&nbsp;p.m.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/03/16/nation/latest-thing-shut-down-due-coronavirus-construction-boston/ | title = Ordinary life in MA is over for now: Walsh orders construction shutdown, tally of cases statewide rises to 197 | website = [[The Boston Globe]] }}</ref>\n\nThe [[MBTA]] announced that starting March 17, it would run subway and buses at Saturday levels of service during the week, with express buses still running, ferries not running, and commuter rail running on a modified schedule.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/03/16/metro/memo-mbta-planning-service-changes-response-coronavirus/ | title = MBTA to reduce train and bus service, close ferry \u2013 The Boston Globe | website = [[The Boston Globe]] }}</ref> The next day, service was increased on the Blue Line, Green Line E branch (which serves Longwood Medical Center), and some bus lines to reduce crowding. Frequency on [[Massport]] shuttles to [[Logan International Airport]] were reduced or canceled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/03/18/metro/t-trying-balance-unhealthy-crowding-with-fewer-cars/|title=T trying to balance unhealthy crowding with fewer cars - The Boston Globe|website=BostonGlobe.com}}</ref>\n\nThe Department of Public Health revised the criteria for recording COVID-19 cases. Per guidance from the CDC, all confirmed or presumptive positive cases are simply categorized as positive, and not differentiated.<ref name=\"Mass-DPH\" /> The daily table published by the DPH also changed, whereas the category for cases associated with the Berkshire Medical Center was replaced with a category for local transmission.<ref group=\"note\">Compare documents in notes for \"MDPH 3/15\" and \"MDPH 3/16\"</ref>\n\nBiogen announced that it would donate $10 million to support global response efforts and communities around the world affected by the COVID-19 pandemic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://investors.biogen.com/news-releases/news-release-details/biogen-foundation-commits-10-million-support-covid-19-relief|title=Biogen Foundation Commits $10 Million to Support COVID-19 Relief Efforts in the U.S. and Around the World|website=Biogen|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, the reported number of coronavirus cases increased 21 from Monday to 218.  The number of hospitalized patients with suspected or known infections quadrupled to 53 between March 16 and 17, as major hospitals began reusing protective gear or asking the public for donations of masks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/03/18/metro/hospitalizations-covid-19-escalate-greater-boston/|title=Hospitalizations for coronavirus escalate in Greater Boston|date=2020-03-17|website=[[The Boston Globe]] }}</ref>\n\n==== March 18\u201321 ====\nOn March 18, the number of cases increased to 256, an increase of 38.  The number of cases where initial exposure was under investigation rose rapidly, whereas cases tracked to Biogen attendees and household contacts continued an overall mild decline.<ref name=\"MDPH_20201903\" group=\"note\"/> On March 19, Governor Baker activated up to 2,000 [[Massachusetts National Guard]] to assist in the management of the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |last=McDonald |first=Danny |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/03/19/nation/baker-activates-national-guard-coronavirus-crisis-grows/ |title=Baker activates National Guard as coronavirus crisis grows |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |date=2020-03-19 |access-date=2020-03-19 }}</ref> The number of cases increased by 72, putting the total at 328, with 119 in [[Middlesex County, Massachusetts|Middlesex County]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcboston.com/news/local/massachusetts-coronavirus-cases-rise-to-328-up-72-in-one-day/2094075/|title=Massachusetts Coronavirus Cases See Largest 1-Day Spike Yet|website=NBC Boston|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>  [[Franklin County, Massachusetts|Franklin]] and [[Hampshire County, Massachusetts|Hampshire]] counties\u2014both in Western Massachusetts and the last non-island counties\u2014had their first confirmed cases of COVID-19.<ref name=\"Mass-DPH\" /> The [[Boston Celtics]] announced that shooting guard [[Marcus Smart]] tested positive for COVID-19 and was in isolation while in treatment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boston.com/sports/boston-celtics/2020/03/19/celtics-coronavirus-test-results|title=Marcus Smart has tested positive for coronavirus|website=Boston.com|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, Massachusetts experienced its first death due to COVID-19.  The fatality was an 87-year-old man from [[Suffolk County, Massachusetts|Suffolk County]], hospitalized and with preexisting heart conditions.<ref name=\"Herald_first_death\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonherald.com/2020/03/20/first-massachusetts-coronavirus-death-in-elderly-man-from-suffolk-county/|title=First Massachusetts coronavirus death is an elderly man from Suffolk County|date=2020-03-20|website=[[Boston Herald]]|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref><ref name=\"Globe_first_death\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/03/20/nation/1st-coronavirus-death-is-reported-massachusetts/|title=Winthrop man, 87, is 1st coronavirus death in Massachusetts as case tally rises to more than 400 - The Boston Globe|website=[[The Boston Globe]] |access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>  Massachusetts authorities announced that 85 new cases of COVID-19 were confirmed in the state bringing the total infections to 413.<ref name=\"413 cases\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcboston.com/news/local/number-of-massachusetts-coronavirus-cases-jumps-to-413/2094757/|title=Number of Massachusetts Coronavirus Cases Jumps to 413|website=NBC Boston|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> Of the total cases, 144 were in Middlesex County.  [[Martha's Vineyard]] in [[Dukes County, Massachusetts|Dukes County]] had its first case, a 50-year-old man in [[Tisbury, Massachusetts|Tisbury]].<ref name=\"Dukes-1st\">{{cite web|url=https://www.mvtimes.com/2020/03/20/confirmed-covid-case/|title=Update: Tisbury resident 'positive' for COVID-19|first=Brian|last=Dowd|date=March 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Tisbury press release for COVID-19|publisher=Town of Tisbury, office of the Board of Health|url=https://www.tisburyma.gov/sites/tisburyma/files/uploads/press_release_covid-19.pdf|date=2020-03-20}}</ref>  This brought coronavirus to 13 of 14 counties in Massachusetts.<ref name=\"413 cases\" /> [[Harvard University]] declared that its 369th Commencement Exercises would be postponed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boston25news.com/news/coronavirus-live-blog-msp-warning-about-covid-19-thefts/WUF4Z3XGGVDVBES6E3WMOCJYRQ/|title=Coronavirus live blog: Confirmed cases jumps to 413, state not planning shelter-in-place order|website=WFXT|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>  The cities of [[Somerville, Massachusetts|Somerville]] and [[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge]] closed non-essential businesses.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.somervillema.gov/departments/programs/novel-coronavirus-preparedness-and-information|title=SomervilleMA.gov Novel Coronavirus Preparedness and Information|access-date=2020-03-21|website=SomervilleMA.gov|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321175543/https://www.somervillema.gov/departments/programs/novel-coronavirus-preparedness-and-information|archive-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cambridgema.gov:443/en/news/2020/03/temporaryemergencyorderontheclosureofseveralbusinessesactivities|title=Cambridge City Manager and Commissioner of Public Health Issue Temporary Emergency Order on the Closure of Several Businesses and Activities|website=www.cambridgema.gov}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Social distancing in a Trader Joe's line in Cambridgeport, Cambridge, Massachusetts March 21, 2020.jpg|thumb|Social distancing in a Trader Joe's line in Cambridgeport, Cambridge, Massachusetts March 21, 2020]]\n[[File:Closed picnic area Natick Turnpike rest area on I-90 during the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Massachusetts.jpg|thumb|Closed picnic area Natick Turnpike rest area on I-90 during the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Massachusetts]]\nOn March 21, the [[Massachusetts Department of Corrections]] (DOC) announced the first confirmed case of COVID-19 among its inmate population. According to officials at [[Massachusetts Treatment Center|MTC Bridgewater,]] a male inmate who was serving a life sentence tested positive.  Massachusetts DOC noted this was the only known case of COVID-19 in its inmate population.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wcvb.com/article/inmate-at-bridgewater-prison-massachusetts-treatment-center-tests-positive-for-coronavirus-officials-say/31846456|title=Inmate at local prison tests positive for coronavirus, officials say|date=2020-03-21|website=WCVB|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref> The number of cases increased by 112 to 525 statewide.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wcvb.com/article/massachusetts-covid-19-coronavirus-update-march-21-2020/31849021|title=Total coronavirus cases climb over 500 in Mass.; includes first on Martha's Vineyard|date=2020-03-21|website=WCVB|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>  Governor Baker announced that 5,207 people had been tested for COVID-19 in Massachusetts through state and commercial laboratories.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wcvb.com/article/massachusetts-covid-19-coronavirus-update-march-21-2020/31849021|title=Total coronavirus cases climb over 500 in Mass.; includes first on Martha's Vineyard|date=March 21, 2020|website=WCVB}}</ref> That night the state announced its second death due to COVID-19, a woman from [[Middlesex County, Massachusetts|Middlesex County]] in her 50s with a preexisting health condition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boston25news.com/news/second-covid-19-related-death-massachusetts-announced/RELZ7F5NWREGBHC7HOJ5QWGXMY/|title=Second COVID-19 related death in Massachusetts announced|website=WFXT}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Croteau |first1=Scott |title=Coronavirus: Ayer woman is second COVID-19 death in Massachusetts, health officials confirm |url=https://www.masslive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-ayer-woman-is-second-covid-19-death-in-massachusetts-health-officials-confirm.html |access-date=22 March 2020 |publisher=MassLive |date=22 March 2020}}</ref> Nantucket County, the last county in Massachusetts to do so, reported its first coronavirus case.<ref name=\"Nantucket-1st\">{{cite web|url=https://www.capecodtimes.com/news/20200320/virus-cases-multiply-on-cape-cod-vineyard|title=Virus cases multiply on Cape Cod, Vineyard|last=McCormick|first=Cynthia|website=capecodtimes.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> In order to reduce contact between drivers and customers, the MBTA began rear-door boarding on surface stops for buses, the Green Line, and the Mattapan Trolley, except for passengers with disabilities who need to use the front door.<ref>[https://www.mbta.com/news/2020-03-20/mbta-announces-service-update-effective-saturday-march-21 MBTA Announces Service Update Effective Saturday, March 21]</ref>\n\n==== March 22\u201325 ====\n\nOn March 22, [[Nantucket]] issued a [[Stay-at-home order|shelter in place order]] starting March 23 and ending on April 6. It will not be a full lockdown, as essential services will remain open.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boston25news.com/news/coronavirus-live-blog-second-mass-resident-dies-covid-19-525-total-cases-across-state/WUF4Z3XGGVDVBES6E3WMOCJYRQ/|title=Coronavirus live blog: Second Mass. resident dies from COVID-19; 525 total cases across state|website=WFXT|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> Governor Baker instructed people on mainland Massachusetts with second homes in [[Nantucket]] and [[Dukes County, Massachusetts|Dukes]] County to stay on mainland.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcboston.com/news/local/mass-gov-baker-to-provide-update-on-coronavirus-response/2095463/|title='Stay on Mainland,' Gov. Baker Tells Residents With 2nd Homes on Nantucket, Vineyard|website=NBC Boston|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> The number of cases increased 121 to reach 646 statewide, with nearly 200 in [[Middlesex County, Massachusetts|Middlesex County]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.westernmassnews.com/news/officials-confirmed-cases-of-coronavirus-in-massachusetts/article_23afbc1e-6ae7-11ea-bbaa-17f1bed2efbf.html|title=Officials: 646 confirmed cases of coronavirus in Massachusetts|last=Trowbridge|first=Ryan|website=WesternMassNews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> Three new deaths were reported by Massachusetts DPH, two men, both in their 70s, from [[Hampden County, Massachusetts|Hampden]] and [[Berkshire County, Massachusetts|Berkshire]] counties, and a man in his 90s from [[Suffolk County, Massachusetts|Suffolk County]].<ref name=\":0\" group=\"note\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcboston.com/news/local/121-new-coronavirus-cases-in-massachusetts-total-jumps-to-646/2095586/|title=Massachusetts Reports 3 More Coronavirus Deaths as Cases Reach 646 Statewide|website=NBC Boston|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, Governor Baker announced his stay-at-home advisory effective March 24 until April 7. Nonessential businesses are ordered to close physical workplaces. People are allowed to go out to obtain essential goods and services such as groceries and medicines, but [[social distancing]] protocols should be followed.<ref name=Feuer>{{cite news |last1=Feuer |first1=William |title=Massachusetts under \"stay-at-home\" order until April 7, Gov. Baker announces |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/23/massachusetts-under-stay-at-home-order-until-april-7-gov-baker-announces.html |access-date=23 March 2020 |work=CNBC |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> The number of cases increased 131 to 777 on March 23. Four new deaths were attributed to COVID-19.<ref group=\"note\" name=\":1\">https://www.mass.gov/doc/covid-19-cases-in-massachusetts-as-of-march-23-2020/download</ref>\n\nOn March 24, the number of cases jumped 382 to 1,159, with two new deaths attributed to COVID-19.<ref name=\"auto\">https://www.mass.gov/doc/covid-19-cases-in-massachusetts-as-of-march-24-2020/download</ref> This unusually large jump in cases (49%, versus 20-28% in the previous five days) was attributable to Quest Laboratories processing 3,843 tests in one day, yielding 267 of the state's 382 new positive results.<ref name=\"Mass-DPH\"/>\n\nOn March 25, the number of cases jumped 679 to 1838, an increase of 59%. Four new deaths were reported by Massachusetts DPH.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcboston.com/news/local/massachusetts-coronavirus-cases-increase-to-1838-15-dead/2097141/|title=Massachusetts Coronavirus Cases Increase to 1,838; 15 Dead|website=NBC Boston|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Governor Baker declared schools closed until May 4.<ref name=\"nbcboston1\"/> The Commissioner of Public Health issued emergency regulations for grocery stores and pharmacies. A daily senior shopping hour, checkout line distancing markers, hand washing and sanitizer for employees, disinfecting wipes for customers to use on carts, and a ban on reusable bags became mandatory, overriding local bans on single-used plastic bags and eliminating bag fees. Self-service food stations were ordered closed, and regular sanitization was required.<ref>[https://www.mass.gov/doc/grocery-and-pharmacy-store-order/download Order of the Commissioner of Public Health, March 25]</ref>\n\n==== March 26\u201331 ====\nOn March 26, the number of cases increased by 579 to a total of 2,417. 10 more deaths were attributed to COVID-19.<ref>https://www.mass.gov/doc/covid-19-cases-in-massachusetts-as-of-march-26-2020/download</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://whdh.com/news/health-officials-579-new-covid-19-cases-in-mass-total-rises-to-2417-with-25-coronavirus-related-deaths/|title=Health officials: 579 new COVID-19 cases in Mass., total rises to 2,417 with 25 coronavirus-related deaths|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> On March 27, 823 new cases were reported, with the total increasing to 3,240. Another 10 people died, putting the number of deaths at 35.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcboston.com/news/local/10-new-deaths-3240-total-cases-of-coronavirus-in-mass/2098439/|title=35 Deaths, Over 3,200 Cases of Coronavirus in Mass.|website=NBC Boston|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> The state extended the tax filing deadline to July 15 and announced new travel guidelines.<ref>{{cite web | title=Baker-Polito Administration Announces Travel Guidelines and New Health Care Resources To Support COVID-19 Response | website=Mass.gov | date=27 March 2020 | url=https://www.mass.gov/news/baker-polito-administration-announces-travel-guidelines-and-new-health-care-resources-to | access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Massachusetts Announces State Income Tax Filing Deadline Being Extended to July 15 | website=Mass.gov | date=27 March 2020 | url=https://www.mass.gov/news/massachusetts-announces-state-income-tax-filing-deadline-being-extended-to-july-15 | access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=Mass. coronavirus cases jump by more than 800, with 10 new related deaths; Baker asks travelers to self-quarantine | website=[[The Boston Globe]] | date=27 March 2020 | url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/03/27/metro/baker-asks-all-travelers-arriving-mass-self-quarantine/ | access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref> State officials announced that the [[Massachusetts Department of Public Health|Massachusetts Department of Public Health Commissioner]], Monica Bharel, had tested positive for COVID-19, had mild symptoms, and would recover at home.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.patriotledger.com/news/20200327/massachusetts-department-of-public-health-commissioner-tests-positive-for-coronavirus |title=Massachusetts Department of Public Health commissioner tests positive for coronavirus - News - The Patriot Ledger, Quincy, MA - Quincy, MA |publisher=Patriotledger.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-01}}</ref> On March 28, over 1000 new cases and 9 new deaths were reported, putting the total number of cases at 4,257. The number of deaths increased to 44.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcboston.com/news/coronavirus/44-deaths-1017-new-cases-covid-19-coronavirus-mass/2098869/|title=Massachusetts' Coronavirus Death Toll at 44, Over 1,000 New Cases Saturday|website=NBC Boston|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\nOn March 29, 4 new deaths and 698 new cases were reported, with the total number of cases increasing to 4,955. The number of deaths increased to 48.<ref>https://www.mass.gov/doc/covid-19-cases-in-massachusetts-as-of-march-29-2020/download</ref> \n\nOn March 30, 797 new cases put the total at 5,752. The death toll increased to 56.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.wbur.org/commonhealth/2020/03/30/massachusetts-coronvirus-cases |title=Mass. Now Has More Than 5,000 Reported Coronavirus Cases &#124; CommonHealth |publisher=Wbur.org |date=2020-03-27 |accessdate=2020-04-01}}</ref>  The state also announced that it has conducted almost 43,000 tests of Massachusetts residents with [[Quest Diagnostics]] having conducted 21,321 or almost half of the total tests administered.<ref>https://www.mass.gov/doc/covid-19-cases-in-massachusetts-as-of-march-30-2020/download</ref>  A potential cluster of COVID-19 cases was reported in [[Holyoke, Massachusetts]] at Soldiers' Home, a nursing facility that cares for retired members of the military.  Eleven residents had recently died, and another 11 residents along with several staff members had tested positive for COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lisinski |first=Chris |url=https://www.wwlp.com/news/local-news/hampden-county/holyoke-soldiers-home-superintendent-placed-on-leave-effective-immediately/ |title=11 veterans dead, several residents, staff exposed to COVID-19 at Holyoke Soldiers\u2019 Home |publisher=WWLP |date= |accessdate=2020-04-01}}</ref>  Later that evening, the [[MBTA]] announced that 18 transit workers had tested positive for COVID-19.<ref>https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/03/30/metro/mbta-unions-looking-more-ways-slow-spread-coronavirus/</ref> In addition, the [[Boston Police Department]] confirmed that 19 uniformed officers and three civilian employees had all tested positive for COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://twitter.com/Tom_Winter/status/1244788245721997315 |title=Tom Winter on Twitter: \"NEW: Boston Police spokesperson John Boyle says 22 BPD members have tested positive for COVID-19, 19 uniformed and 3 civilians. This updates an earlier tweet.\" |publisher=Twitter.com |date=2009-03-27 |accessdate=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nOn March 31, 868 new cases were reported, putting the running total at 6,620. 33 new deaths were reported, with the total jumping to 89.<ref>https://www.mass.gov/doc/covid-19-cases-in-massachusetts-as-of-march-31-2020/download</ref>\n\n== Epidemiology ==\n=== Diagrams ===\n<gallery widths=\"333\" heights=\"150\" mode=\"packed\" style=\"text-align: left;\" caption=\"Massachusetts COVID-19 cases by category as of March 31\">\nFile:Massachusetts COVID-19 total cases.svg|Total reported cases\nFile:Massachusetts COVID-19 tests by laboratory total patients tested.svg|Total tests, by laboratory\nFile:Massachusetts COVID-19 cases by exposure.svg|Cases by exposure<ref group=\"note\">Massachusetts Department of Public Health last reported contact tracing on March 27.</ref>\nFile:Massachusetts COVID-19 cases by percent hospitalized.svg|Cases by percent hospitalized\nFile:Massachusetts COVID-19 cases by age group.svg|Cases by age group\nFile:Massachusetts COVID-19 Deaths by Age Group.svg|Deaths by age group\nFile:COVID-19 cases in Massachusetts by county map.svg|Cases by county as of March 31{{Col-begin}}{{Col-2}}{{legend|#C8C8C8|0}}{{legend|#FFE4A3|1\u20139}}{{legend|#F2A88D|10\u201349}}{{Col-2}}{{legend|#E57814|50\u2013199}}{{legend|#FF0000|200\u2013499}}{{legend|#A81C1B|&#8805; 500}}{{Col-end}}  \n</gallery>\n\n=== Initial exposures and spread ===\nThe [[index case]] of COVID-19 in Massachusetts was reported on February 1, 2020 in Boston.  The patient, a man in his 20s and [[University of Massachusetts Boston]] student, had recently returned to Boston from [[Wuhan]], China.<ref name=\"Wertheim\" />  The second case in Massachusetts was reported on March 2.  The patient was a woman in her 20s from [[Norfolk County]], who had recently traveled to Italy with a school group from [[Saint Raphael Academy]] in [[Pawtucket, Rhode Island|Pawtucket]], [[Rhode Island]].<ref name=\"WBUR-2nd\" />  After a month of stasis, cases began growing rapidly on March 5, with most traceable to a [[Biogen]] conference held in at the Marriott Long Wharf hotel in Boston from February 26\u201328.<ref group=\"note\">See [[#Cases by category|Cases by category]] table.</ref>\n\nExposure clusters were reported from mid to late March.  Local [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] began being reported on March 16, slightly exceeding cases related to travel.<ref group=\"note\" name=\":9\"/>  An outbreak cluster of untraced origin in [[Berkshire Medical Center]] in Western Massachusetts was briefly tracked from March 11 through March 15. Cases that had been [[contact tracing|contact-traced]] to Biogen plateaued on March 13, and were surpassed by local transmissions on March 23.  Cases of unknown exposure surpassed those of known exposure on March 19, then grew rapidly.  When the [[Massachusetts Department of Public Health]] ceased updating statistics on exposure on March 27, there were 99 cases traced to Biogen, 163 cases of local transmission, 93 cases related to travel, and 2,885 cases where initial exposure was under investigation.<ref group=\"note\" name=\":17\"/>\n\nThe disease went undetected after entering Boston in Suffolk County in early February.  It then re-emerged in early March and spread to the state's remaining 13 counties within three weeks.  Suffolk County had its first reported case on February 1,<ref name=\"Wertheim\" /> Norfolk County on March 2,<ref name=\"WBUR-2nd\" /> Middlesex County on March 6,<ref group=\"note\" name=\":6\"/> Berkshire County on March 7,<ref name=\"WHDH-Berkshire-1st\"/> Essex County on March 10,<ref name=\"Tribune-Essex-1st\"/> Barnstable and Worcester counties on March 14,<ref name=\"Barnstable-1st\"/><ref name=\"Worcester-1st\"/> Hampden and Plymouth counties on March 15,<ref name=\"Hampden-1st\"/><ref name=\"Plymouth-1st\"/> Franklin and Hampshire counties on March 19,<ref name=\"MDPH_20201903\" group=\"note\"/> Dukes County on March 20,<ref name=\"Dukes-1st\"/> and Nantucket County on March 21.<ref name=\"Nantucket-1st\"/>\n\n=== Hospitalizations ===\nBetween 6% and 14% of COVID-19 cases in Massachusetts were known to be hospitalized.<ref group=\"note\">See \"[[#Diagrams|Cases by percent hospitalized\" diagram]].</ref>  The first 4 [[hospitalization]]s were reported on March 9.<ref group=\"note\" name=\":5\"/>  The number of hospitalizations surpassed 10 on March 12,<ref group=\"note\" name=\":2\"/> 100 on March 25,<ref group=\"note\" name=\":20\"/> and 500 on March 31.<ref group=\"note\" name=\":21\"/>  The number of cases with unknown hospitalization status exceeded those with a known status on March 23.<ref group=\"note\" name=\":18\"/>\n\n=== Deaths ===\nDeaths due to COVID-19 were concentrated among the elderly.  As of March 31, 75 of 89 (84%) COVID-19 deaths were in patients aged 70 or older, and no one younger than 50 was known to have died from the disease in Massachusetts.<ref group=\"note\" name=\"See-deaths-by-age\">See \"[[#Diagrams|Deaths by age group]]\" chart.</ref>  The state's first death due to COVID-19 was on March 20.  The patient was a 87-year-old man from Suffolk County, hospitalized and with preexisting heart conditions.<ref name=\"Herald_first_death\"/><ref name=\"Globe_first_death\"/>\n\n=== Cases by category ===\nThe Massachusetts Department of Public Health published daily updates on COVID-19 in Massachusetts, beginning on March 6, 2020.  Local media and the state also published intermittent reports beforehand.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-datatable sortable\" style=\"text-align: right; font-size: 0.9em;\"\n! colspan=\"20\" | Coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) cases in Massachusetts<ref name=\"Mass-DPH\" />\n|-\n! | \n! colspan=\"5\" style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" | Total\n! colspan=\"4\" style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" | Exposure\n! colspan=\"3\" style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" | Tests\n! colspan=\"3\" style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" | Hospitalization\n! colspan=\"3\" style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" | Deaths\n! style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" |\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" style=\"width:70px; border-right:2px solid #888;\"| Date\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" {{vert header|Confirmed}} <!-- can we please add number of days it takes for cases to double and number of days to multiply by 10 (log)? --->\n! scope=\"col\" {{vert header|stp=1|Change}}\n! scope=\"col\" {{vert header|stp=1|% change}}\n! class=\"unsortable\" {{vert he